WEBVTT

00:15.682 --> 00:23.253
Well, hey, if you've been tracking along with the Olympics, then you know the games ended in stunning fashion this past Sunday.

00:23.373 --> 00:25.215
Some of you know what I'm talking about for others of you though.

00:25.616 --> 00:26.938
You may be uninformed.

00:26.958 --> 00:29.942
So let me do you a great kindness in informing you.

00:29.962 --> 00:34.368
The US men's hockey team.

00:36.171 --> 00:38.935
One gold in stellar fashion.

00:40.617 --> 00:44.242
Stellar fashion because this is the first gold medal we've picked up in the last

00:44.418 --> 00:46.381
46 years, yes, you heard me, right?

00:46.401 --> 00:53.253
The last 46 years, yes, it has been roughly half a century since we found ourselves in the gold medal match.

00:53.754 --> 01:05.554
We were then at that time accustomed to people like Coach Herb Brooks and all those young boys that performed the miracle on ice as we took on the undefeatable Soviet Union, and yet we did the impossible then.

01:05.574 --> 01:08.178
Wouldn't you know we did the impossible

01:08.258 --> 01:12.143
Again, but that's not the only thing that's amazing about this last weekend.

01:12.444 --> 01:15.267
It's not just that we won gold after 46 years.

01:15.548 --> 01:18.872
It's also the way in which we won gold in overtime.

01:20.394 --> 01:25.160
And what was just a little over a minute when all hope seemed lost.

01:26.322 --> 01:35.634
One young man by the name of Jack Hughes decided to take matters into his own hands and seal the deal and score the golden gold.

01:36.706 --> 01:37.628
for our country.

01:37.648 --> 01:39.151
It was an amazing event.

01:40.694 --> 01:50.813
And yet, though it is remarkable that Jack Hughes did this, it's also remarkable to know that he wasn't alone.

01:50.893 --> 01:55.602
Jack is one of two brothers that plays on the US men's hockey team.

01:56.002 --> 01:59.726
His brother Quinn Hughes also serves on the hockey team as a defenseman.

01:59.806 --> 02:07.135
And so when I learned that he wasn't alone, that Quinn is in there as well, I had to ask the question, how is Quinn dealing with all of this?

02:08.316 --> 02:12.140
Baby brother swoops in, it steals the glory for himself.

02:13.302 --> 02:24.274
And I was shocked to find as is much of the country that Quinn, who is such a class act, has just expressed the utmost admiration and pride towards his brother.

02:25.122 --> 02:26.384
He said this in an interview.

02:26.424 --> 02:28.206
He said, I'm just so proud of him.

02:29.168 --> 02:31.691
People have no idea how hard this journey has been for him.

02:32.012 --> 02:39.723
Dealing with injuries and battling through so much to be the player that he is, he's one of the best players in the world and I'm so glad that everybody got to see why today.

02:39.763 --> 02:42.126
He's just a dog.

02:44.670 --> 02:53.362
And a post later on that he commented after sharing it alongside Sports Center and ESPN, he simply said one word.

02:54.562 --> 02:57.865
to surmise his thoughts around his brother, Jack.

02:57.885 --> 03:01.028
And it was beneath this photo that he said, hero.

03:03.751 --> 03:13.600
You see, our nation has been stunned since Sunday, not just because the US men's hockey team did something that was unimaginable.

03:13.640 --> 03:15.281
They stepped in and they won gold.

03:15.321 --> 03:17.003
Yes, that is so shocking.

03:17.263 --> 03:24.530
But we have also been shocked by the way in which Quinn has responded to the success of his brother.

03:24.674 --> 03:30.034
He has been a class act, as I've already said, and yet at the same time, what we know is this has got to be hard.

03:30.626 --> 03:36.391
Like all of us are reading through the comments and trying to ascertain, man, what do we all really think about this?

03:36.451 --> 03:46.900
Because, man, when you are arguably the more decorated skater, you are the older brother, and yet your brother has swept in and he has stolen the glory.

03:46.980 --> 03:48.281
How are you dealing with that?

03:48.722 --> 03:54.647
And yet as he has responded so admirably, it has left the nation speechless.

03:54.727 --> 04:00.612
We're trying to reckon with how one man could respond in the way in which he has, because we know this

04:00.592 --> 04:01.493
would be difficult.

04:02.895 --> 04:05.679
And the reason we know it is because we've lived it.

04:06.581 --> 04:13.250
We've found ourselves in positions where we're looking at our own set of circumstances, and we've evaluated differently than he did.

04:13.551 --> 04:16.175
We've evaluated, this isn't fair.

04:17.036 --> 04:18.318
This feels crazy.

04:18.378 --> 04:19.520
It doesn't make any sense.

04:19.820 --> 04:21.082
I'm totally misunderstood.

04:21.102 --> 04:23.045
Things didn't play out the way that I thought.

04:23.746 --> 04:29.394
You see, according to one study by the Edelman Trust Barometer, which evaluates fairness and opportunity in the United States,

04:29.698 --> 04:34.085
Catch this, 83%, that would be the vast majority of our room.

04:34.145 --> 04:42.719
Eight out of 10 of you, young adults, 18 to 34-year-olds reported feeling subjected to unfair treatment in some way in their life.

04:44.201 --> 04:54.738
Feeling discriminated against, whether it's at work or it's in their social sphere or it's in the marketplace in some way, which is something we all understand because whether you're working hard,

04:54.850 --> 05:06.503
You still can't afford rent or you're reminded via social media often that outcomes in other people's lives rarely actually match their effort or you and your ex have very different responses after the breakup.

05:06.543 --> 05:13.691
They're thriving while you're still healing or you're just quietly quitting on the job because your boss overworks you but undervalues you.

05:14.012 --> 05:20.619
We can't help but agree with what that great 21st century philosopher, Olivia Rodrigo said.

05:22.041 --> 05:23.282
God, it's brutal out here.

05:24.706 --> 05:30.234
In a study, ABC News found that only 21% of US adults believe in the American dream.

05:30.254 --> 05:31.276
21%.

05:31.616 --> 05:40.429
It has stunned researchers to hear our generation lean in and say, that doesn't feel legitimate any longer.

05:40.489 --> 05:51.666
So as they've tried to make reason as to why we think the American dream is in fact just a dream, they have asked us and what we have said in response is that idealized life.

05:53.410 --> 05:54.892
just is not fair.

05:57.755 --> 06:02.040
It feels unrealistic because life is unrealistic.

06:02.060 --> 06:02.781
Life is unfair.

06:02.821 --> 06:14.434
It doesn't matter if you want to call it burnout, if you want to call it hard mode, if you want to call it character development, if you want to call it late stage capitalism, or if you just want to believe that the algorithm hates you, everyone is saying the same thing just through different words.

06:14.474 --> 06:18.418
We think life is not fair, which is easier to accept if

06:18.498 --> 06:19.479
You don't believe in God.

06:19.499 --> 06:27.029
And you just think that everything that's happening around you is the accidental byproduct of some random processes, but it is much more difficult if you do believe in God.

06:28.211 --> 06:29.493
Because you know nothing is accidental.

06:30.274 --> 06:31.275
Everything is purposeful.

06:31.535 --> 06:35.140
That there is a sovereign supreme, a creator of the cosmos.

06:35.160 --> 06:39.306
That this God whom we say we believe in is supposed to be the giver of every good and perfect gift.

06:39.326 --> 06:45.714
And yet as we look at the world around us and we consider the life that we live, we know something just doesn't make sense.

06:46.882 --> 06:49.245
And it's not just that life doesn't feel fair.

06:50.927 --> 06:52.129
It's that he doesn't feel fair.

06:54.131 --> 06:55.313
What do you do with that?

06:57.115 --> 06:58.677
Well, that's what Genesis 4 is all about.

06:59.177 --> 07:00.679
So if you have a Bible, you can grab it.

07:00.699 --> 07:02.522
You can turn with me to Genesis chapter 4.

07:02.562 --> 07:04.905
If this is your first time to the porch, welcome.

07:05.025 --> 07:05.886
We're so glad you're here.

07:06.066 --> 07:13.575
We've been working through a series in the book of Genesis where we're looking at 10 of the most iconic stories found within its pages.

07:13.595 --> 07:15.698
And the reason why is we want to

07:16.066 --> 07:20.612
acquaint ourselves, for many of us reacquaint ourselves with who God is.

07:20.632 --> 07:27.862
And as we study this first book in the Bible, we see each of these stories telling us different aspects of our Lord.

07:28.723 --> 07:32.769
And as we come to this story, we find ourselves, and yet again, another familiar one.

07:32.789 --> 07:35.272
We find ourselves looking at the story of Cain and Abel.

07:35.352 --> 07:39.278
This is the first sibling rivalry in human history.

07:39.799 --> 07:43.524
I don't know how you feel about your siblings, but these guys had some beef.

07:44.445 --> 07:45.266
And as we look,

07:45.666 --> 07:48.869
is that many of us approach this story with a different perspective.

07:48.889 --> 07:54.235
Some of you, you've read this story, you're actually really familiar with it, and so you approach it systematically.

07:54.295 --> 08:00.261
You theologically unpack and think through the essence of total depravity that is expressed by way of its pages.

08:00.862 --> 08:03.144
Others of you, you're vaguely familiar.

08:03.945 --> 08:09.691
You know the broad strokes, and you know that this story lines up like some sort of ancient Near Eastern soap opera.

08:09.811 --> 08:12.434
One brother kills another brother, and you're not real sure what happened, but man,

08:13.250 --> 08:14.772
as goes and all God's children.

08:15.073 --> 08:23.425
Others of you, you think about this story and what comes to mind when you think of Cain and Abel is what came to mind in the mind of one of my staff people, which is raising Cain's.

08:24.667 --> 08:30.736
Which interestingly is a phrase of speech that finds its historical origin in Cain and Abel, but we won't go there for now.

08:31.096 --> 08:40.530
What you need to understand is that though we all read this story and hear something different, many of us, most of us, do not hear our story.

08:41.378 --> 08:43.320
when we read Cain's story.

08:44.121 --> 08:47.966
The reason why is because it just feels so unrelatable.

08:47.986 --> 08:49.288
It feels even primeval.

08:49.368 --> 08:52.011
It doesn't feel practical in the slightest because he's a murderer and I'm not.

08:52.872 --> 09:00.902
And yet here's what I would argue with you because, as already said, I'm coming in as someone that has been touched by this text myself.

09:03.845 --> 09:08.671
This story, it isn't just Cain's story.

09:10.133 --> 09:10.994
It's our.

09:11.586 --> 09:12.007
story.

09:13.048 --> 09:33.897
And I want us to read it as such because what we're going to find as we read through this is we're going to see that his story, our story, is one that speaks to this really unfair fact that God himself at times doesn't feel fair.

09:35.760 --> 09:36.400
So what are we doing?

09:36.420 --> 09:36.941
That's the case.

09:36.961 --> 09:37.802
That's what I want to tell you.

09:37.923 --> 09:39.004
So let's just look at it.

09:39.024 --> 09:40.466
We're going to go a little by little and we're going to talk.

09:41.218 --> 09:45.805
Verse 1, Now Adam do Eve his wife.

09:46.846 --> 09:50.632
And she conceived and she bore Cain saying, I've gotten a man with the help of the Lord.

09:50.652 --> 09:52.375
And again, she bore his brother Abel.

09:52.415 --> 09:55.820
Now Abel was a keeper of sheep and Cain a worker of the ground.

09:55.840 --> 09:59.425
And in the course of time Cain brought to the Lord an offering of the fruit of the ground.

10:00.147 --> 10:02.450
And Abel also brought of the first born of his flock.

10:02.882 --> 10:03.823
and of their fat portions.

10:03.843 --> 10:07.266
Now, we'll just stop there because we need to understand something important about this text.

10:07.366 --> 10:11.449
Namely, before we get to any of the conflict, we need to understand the characters.

10:11.530 --> 10:14.112
We just met several, but there's two that we want to zoom in on.

10:14.132 --> 10:16.974
We want to zoom in on these two brothers, Cain and Abel.

10:17.014 --> 10:22.159
What we know is that Cain is the older of the two brothers, which in the ancient Near East would actually come with it.

10:22.639 --> 10:24.581
Many important would come with it.

10:25.281 --> 10:26.482
Much significant detail.

10:26.523 --> 10:31.607
What we know as a first born in their culture is that Cain would have really two privileges.

10:31.647 --> 10:32.868
Number one, he would be

10:32.848 --> 10:36.975
the primary beneficiary of his family's inheritance.

10:37.796 --> 10:46.130
In the number two, we would know that he is the representative male head in place of his father, should his father pass, or his father's just absent.

10:46.510 --> 10:50.637
He would become the representative head of the family, ensuring the family's legacy.

10:50.657 --> 10:53.682
You see, Cain is sort of like the first Nepo baby ever.

10:54.594 --> 10:59.220
He had it easier than most everybody else.

10:59.320 --> 11:00.823
It was just his by way of birthright.

11:01.143 --> 11:05.389
He was the guy that you knew in high school that everybody loved to hate.

11:06.230 --> 11:07.512
He had ridiculous genes.

11:07.552 --> 11:09.314
He played varsity when nobody else did.

11:09.374 --> 11:12.699
He never studied, but always seemed to make straight A's.

11:12.739 --> 11:14.922
He was a foot taller than the rest of us.

11:15.022 --> 11:16.063
I don't have any bitterness you do.

11:16.544 --> 11:23.794
And yet what we know is that regardless that it may have been God-given, he nonetheless deserved to be respected.

11:24.002 --> 11:27.648
He deserved to be honored and he deserved to be privileged.

11:28.089 --> 11:29.191
It's just by way of who he was.

11:29.251 --> 11:34.741
And yet therein lies the first lesson you must know if you want to understand why God feels unfair at times.

11:34.761 --> 11:43.877
You have to know God feels unfair at times when we focus too much on what we deserve and too little on what God deserves.

11:45.419 --> 11:46.962
God will feel unfair.

11:47.714 --> 11:52.027
when you focus too much on what you deserve and too little on what he deserves.

11:52.047 --> 11:57.503
We can tell that this is the case just by way of looking at their offerings in contrast to one another.

11:58.727 --> 11:59.730
You see, Cain,

12:00.130 --> 12:05.137
He brings what the text says is an offering of the fruit of the ground, which is a legitimate offering.

12:05.177 --> 12:09.703
He brings what Leviticus 2 tells us is a serial or a grain offering.

12:09.723 --> 12:14.790
And yet what's really unique about grain offerings is they're unlike any other offering in Leviticus.

12:14.870 --> 12:20.378
We know that they're not bound by strict rigid, they're not bound by rigidity or rules.

12:20.438 --> 12:25.745
There's some flexibility in how you can actually express this offering because it was considered a free will offering.

12:26.366 --> 12:29.170
The thought there being that you could offer to God

12:29.762 --> 12:35.949
What she wanted, however much she wanted, which should beg a question in our mind, okay?

12:35.969 --> 12:40.595
Well, then how much did Cain actually want to give to God?

12:42.858 --> 12:46.001
He gives an indistinct bundle of produce.

12:47.043 --> 12:49.806
It's legitimate, but it's not very detailed.

12:50.727 --> 12:55.593
Whereas in contrast, we look at Abel who brought the first born of his flock and their fat portions.

12:55.613 --> 12:56.594
Do you see the difference?

12:56.802 --> 12:57.955
There's just more detail.

12:57.996 --> 13:00.626
He gives the first born of his flock.

13:00.802 --> 13:03.765
Like he gives the strength of those little Lamys.

13:03.785 --> 13:10.510
He raised of the very first one, that one which would have been useful for resourcing, for wool and for mating and eventually for food.

13:10.530 --> 13:17.957
He takes it and he offers it to God and he gives to God the fat portions, like that most nourishing and precious part of the animal.

13:18.017 --> 13:19.418
He offers it to God.

13:19.438 --> 13:22.301
He doesn't show up to God and offer him a USDA select sirloin.

13:22.341 --> 13:23.282
He says, hey, you know what?

13:23.362 --> 13:24.422
I've got the wagyu ribeye.

13:24.443 --> 13:25.183
Here you go, God.

13:25.203 --> 13:29.707
He offers him the very best thing that he can because God likes that cut.

13:30.027 --> 13:30.788
And what we see

13:30.768 --> 13:35.515
is that God has favor for Abel by way of what he offers.

13:36.336 --> 13:37.718
I love the way that Richard Hess says it.

13:37.738 --> 13:46.291
He says, by giving the firstborn and the best of the animal, the fat, Abel would be understood as having given everything to God.

13:47.433 --> 13:47.873
Do you see it?

13:49.836 --> 13:55.444
Cain gives something to God, while Abel gives everything to God.

13:57.588 --> 13:59.250
And here's the lesson that you need to know.

14:00.802 --> 14:08.633
You can tell a lot about the offeror by way of their offering.

14:10.015 --> 14:14.782
You can tell a lot about the offeror by way of their offering.

14:14.922 --> 14:26.258
I learned this lesson very plainly just two weeks ago when I and every other husband in DFW arose at the crack of dawn and visited a local grocery store because it was Valentine's Day and we needed to buy our wives flowers.

14:27.170 --> 14:27.931
It's quite the sight.

14:28.412 --> 14:36.244
It's just a bunch of men walking around the floral department trying to pick out whatever they think their wife might like.

14:36.525 --> 14:39.329
And as I'm there, I run into a guy that goes to church here at Watermark.

14:39.349 --> 14:42.715
And so we strike up a conversation and ask him, hey, man, what's the plan for the day?

14:43.376 --> 14:45.699
And he looks at me with all of his kids in tow.

14:45.739 --> 14:50.206
And he says, well, we've already sent Mama for a little bit of a spa day, give her a little bit of me time.

14:50.226 --> 14:51.989
And me and the kids are getting her some flowers.

14:52.009 --> 14:54.994
And we're going to go make some homemade Valentine's cards.

14:55.586 --> 15:06.906
And as he said this to me, I thought to myself, that's a man that knows what his woman loves because the offering says a lot about the offeror.

15:08.248 --> 15:10.853
So let me ask you this, what are you offering to God?

15:12.396 --> 15:13.538
What are you offering to him?

15:15.200 --> 15:16.262
Would you offer him today?

15:16.322 --> 15:18.386
Would you offer him this week?

15:19.138 --> 15:21.020
What did you offer him with respect to your time?

15:21.041 --> 15:23.684
Like did you give him your time just whenever it was convenient?

15:23.704 --> 15:27.289
Or did you give him your time whenever it wasn't convenient?

15:28.971 --> 15:34.378
When it came to the scripture, did you take the easy route and let someone else explain to you whatever it is that God might have said?

15:34.638 --> 15:43.170
Or did you go the hard route, study them on your own, meditate even when it was difficult because you don't want to hear what someone has to say.

15:43.210 --> 15:46.514
God might have said, you want to hear what he has to say himself.

15:48.706 --> 15:49.447
What about prayer?

15:50.689 --> 15:53.733
Did you treat prayer like it's just the last resort?

15:55.054 --> 16:06.369
Or did you treat prayer like it was the first response whenever that thing happened this week, that problem popped up out of nowhere, whatever trouble seemed to arise and you did not know what to do.

16:06.569 --> 16:08.752
Did you pray as your first response?

16:11.396 --> 16:16.402
Do you walk into rooms like this and different about the thought of meeting with God?

16:18.082 --> 16:23.348
Or do you walk into rooms like this expectant that God wants to meet with you?

16:25.912 --> 16:26.672
Do you worship?

16:28.214 --> 16:29.276
This might be too personal.

16:31.518 --> 16:35.003
Do you worship in a way where all of your attention is just about you?

16:35.023 --> 16:36.645
I don't want to stand out.

16:37.105 --> 16:37.966
I don't want to sound weird.

16:38.527 --> 16:39.288
I don't want to look bad.

16:39.909 --> 16:43.373
Or do you worship in a way where all of your attention is about him?

16:44.754 --> 16:46.156
What are you offering to God?

16:46.777 --> 16:47.698
How much?

16:47.778 --> 16:49.400
Are you offering to God?

16:49.580 --> 16:49.781
Abel?

16:50.121 --> 16:51.443
Abel brings the first fruit.

16:52.324 --> 16:54.407
He brings the very best of what he has to give.

16:54.467 --> 17:01.136
He gives the fat portion to God because he knows God is worth everything and we have to know the same thing.

17:01.156 --> 17:02.378
You see, here's the problem.

17:02.718 --> 17:07.244
Often we accuse God of not being fair to us when we are guilty of not being fair to him.

17:08.486 --> 17:09.307
You tracking with that?

17:09.968 --> 17:12.492
Like we often look at God and we're like, where are you at God?

17:13.152 --> 17:14.354
You're not being fair to me.

17:14.658 --> 17:22.670
And yet the reality is, if we look at our time, we examine our calendar, we pay attention to our transactions, we would realize we're the ones that's not being fair to him.

17:23.431 --> 17:27.738
We would offer him something when he actually deserves everything.

17:27.818 --> 17:29.540
That's what we see all throughout the scripture.

17:29.560 --> 17:41.298
Revelation 4, 11 says, worthy are you a Lord and God to receive glory and honor and power for you created all things and by your will.

17:41.826 --> 17:43.949
They existed and were created.

17:44.049 --> 17:44.570
Do you hear it?

17:44.590 --> 17:56.889
1 Timothy 1, 17, now to the king eternal, immortal, invisible, the only God be honored and glory forever and ever.

17:57.490 --> 17:58.011
Amen.

17:58.973 --> 18:10.290
Romans 11, 36, for from him and through him and to him are all things, to him and him alone.

18:10.594 --> 18:12.997
be glory forever and ever amen.

18:13.798 --> 18:15.420
Are you tracking with what this is saying?

18:17.522 --> 18:28.976
So why then, Christian, if you are a member of the family of God, if you identify as a follower of Jesus, if you believe these things are true, why is it that you're living with a calculated devotion?

18:30.638 --> 18:37.266
Were you give to God some part of yourself, maybe even most of yourself, but you don't give to God every part of yourself.

18:37.467 --> 18:40.210
You think Christ went to the cross just to die for some part of you?

18:41.218 --> 18:44.742
No, Christ went to the cross to die for every part of you.

18:45.203 --> 18:50.730
And the reason we know that is because he didn't just give up some part of himself, he gave up all of himself.

18:51.591 --> 18:59.941
If that's the case, if he would willingly offer all of himself to you, why then can we not offer all of ourself to him in return?

19:01.163 --> 19:10.514
This is the issue we think God is unfair when we, in fact, are unfair because the fairest thing we could do

19:11.554 --> 19:12.736
is give him everything we've got.

19:14.017 --> 19:14.819
That's your first point.

19:15.740 --> 19:17.042
Second, we find in verse four.

19:18.183 --> 19:20.306
And the Lord had regard for Abel and his offering.

19:21.308 --> 19:23.991
But for Cain and his offering, he had no regard.

19:25.133 --> 19:27.156
So Cain was very angry in his face fell.

19:28.037 --> 19:29.840
The Lord said, Cain, why are you angry?

19:30.701 --> 19:31.862
Why is your face fallen?

19:32.964 --> 19:34.867
If you do well, will you not be accepted?

19:35.788 --> 19:38.772
And if you do not do well, sin is crouching at the door.

19:38.872 --> 19:40.114
It's desires for you.

19:41.058 --> 19:42.059
and you must rule over it.

19:43.640 --> 19:47.844
So both Cain and Abel, they bring offerings to God, yes?

19:48.545 --> 19:53.610
And yet what we just saw is that God only regards Abel's offering.

19:54.671 --> 19:56.012
It's kind of a weird word, right?

19:56.372 --> 19:57.193
God regarded.

19:57.253 --> 20:10.866
Well, if you look in the Hebrew, the idea behind that word regarded is he looked or he gazed upon, not just the offering, he actually gazes upon Abel and Abel's offering, which feels unfair.

20:11.330 --> 20:14.173
Because again, Cain first born.

20:14.893 --> 20:23.081
And so his responsibility as one of the representative heads of the family is to present offerings to God as his father would.

20:23.882 --> 20:26.685
And yet here's Abel doing the same thing.

20:28.726 --> 20:30.268
And it's Abel that God seems to regard.

20:30.388 --> 20:31.569
He's the one that he looks at.

20:32.190 --> 20:32.810
But Cain isn't.

20:33.111 --> 20:34.652
That feels so unfair of God.

20:34.672 --> 20:38.356
And yet we have to ask the question, then was there something wrong with Cain's offering?

20:39.196 --> 20:39.356
No.

20:40.538 --> 20:40.978
Again,

20:41.122 --> 20:42.865
Cain's offering is totally suitable.

20:43.767 --> 20:44.689
It's a serial offering.

20:44.729 --> 20:45.791
It's a grain offering.

20:45.851 --> 20:48.255
It's perfectly legit to give to God.

20:48.496 --> 20:55.268
It doesn't mean that there was something wrong with Cain's offering, but catch this, it does mean that there was something right about Abel's offering.

20:57.192 --> 21:02.642
So several years ago, Brooke and I, we were in Florence, Italy, and we were walking through the academia gallery.

21:03.138 --> 21:11.786
If you're familiar with the academia, then what you know is most people go to the academia not to see all of the marble sculptures that they have littered across their premises.

21:11.826 --> 21:15.010
And they are incredible sculptures within their own right.

21:15.030 --> 21:18.373
But people don't go there for all the myriad of other sculptures.

21:18.393 --> 21:20.675
They go there for one sculpture and one sculpture alone.

21:20.735 --> 21:22.457
They go there for Michelangelo's David.

21:23.538 --> 21:25.440
And it's not because the other sculptures are bad.

21:25.480 --> 21:27.362
The other sculptures are good.

21:29.884 --> 21:31.986
But David is better.

21:33.474 --> 21:41.144
You see, David is greater than the rest because though they are good, he is great.

21:42.166 --> 21:44.068
And that's what's happening here.

21:44.088 --> 21:48.174
You see, Cain has not been rejected by God in this moment.

21:50.257 --> 21:54.002
Abel is merely being favored by God in this moment.

21:55.764 --> 22:02.834
And yet, in this moment, Cain experiences the entirety of what's happening

22:04.354 --> 22:05.696
as personal rejection.

22:07.098 --> 22:19.779
That's why comparison is so very, that's why comparison is so very costly because Cain doesn't realize what we need to realize that favor for somebody else does not mean disfavor for you.

22:21.923 --> 22:26.030
Favor for somebody else does not mean disfavor for you.

22:26.070 --> 22:28.273
That was Cain's experience.

22:28.313 --> 22:31.218
It says that he grew angry and his face dropped.

22:31.426 --> 22:32.127
I love that.

22:32.147 --> 22:33.889
Like you can just picture what's happening to him.

22:33.909 --> 22:35.130
That idea, he grew angry.

22:35.150 --> 22:37.854
It's the thought of him getting heated anger.

22:37.894 --> 22:39.215
Like his blood starts to boil.

22:39.255 --> 22:40.897
He gets hot is what happens.

22:41.117 --> 22:44.662
And then it says that his face drops, like his face falls.

22:45.923 --> 22:51.970
And yet what's happening is you see those two images like a little kid who crosses his arms and ducks his head and starts muttering under his breath.

22:52.471 --> 22:54.413
What we realize is two things are true of him.

22:54.433 --> 22:58.578
In this moment, he is both vindictive and he is victimized.

22:59.234 --> 23:05.004
Which is a really potent mix because what it tells us is he feels like he didn't get what he deserved.

23:06.987 --> 23:09.331
And he's willing to do something about it.

23:09.351 --> 23:13.698
He's willing to take action to honor the injustice he feels like he has suffered.

23:14.379 --> 23:23.194
That's what makes comparison so dangerous because often we internalize somebody else's success as our own personal failure.

23:24.576 --> 23:25.778
And yet that's just not true.

23:26.594 --> 23:29.417
Like just because somebody gets promoted doesn't mean that your boss hates you.

23:30.378 --> 23:34.143
Just because you have a friend who starts dating somebody doesn't mean that nobody wants you.

23:35.144 --> 23:39.409
Just because you see somebody succeed doesn't mean that they're a threat to you.

23:39.589 --> 23:45.856
Just because you're scrolling through Instagram a little bit too long and you realize that everybody's moving ahead doesn't mean that you're left behind.

23:46.377 --> 23:52.684
What we do is we in the process of comparing we often find ourselves growing in resentment.

23:53.245 --> 23:54.226
What's resentment?

23:54.530 --> 23:58.675
Reseminent is not just wanting what other people have, it's hating them for having it.

23:59.917 --> 24:03.041
And yet comparison often breeds this type of response.

24:03.562 --> 24:05.204
That's what the author of Hebrew writes.

24:05.264 --> 24:11.332
He writes in Hebrews chapter 12, strive for peace with everyone and for the holiness without which no one will see the Lord.

24:11.733 --> 24:22.066
See to it that no one fails to obtain the grace of God, that no root of bitterness springs up and causes trouble.

24:22.754 --> 24:24.457
and by it many become defiled.

24:26.019 --> 24:26.980
What's the author saying?

24:28.703 --> 24:35.473
He's saying that our issue is not the fruit of resentment.

24:36.455 --> 24:40.381
What they have, how much they have, what they achieve, what you can't seem to.

24:40.421 --> 24:45.589
Our issue is not the fruit of resentment, it's the root of resentment.

24:46.951 --> 24:51.538
And when we evaluate the root of resentment, what we need to know is that our issue is not with anybody else,

24:52.386 --> 24:54.068
Our issue is with God.

24:55.751 --> 24:57.133
That's the truth of it.

24:57.834 --> 25:07.267
If you find yourself boiling and brooding because they've got something that you think you deserve, your issue is not with them.

25:08.549 --> 25:09.910
Your issue is with Him.

25:09.950 --> 25:15.378
You see, that's what we realize as we study through this thing.

25:16.034 --> 25:18.797
We realize that Cain feels like many of us do.

25:18.837 --> 25:19.518
He feels cheated.

25:19.558 --> 25:20.339
He feels mistreated.

25:20.379 --> 25:21.861
He feels underappreciated.

25:21.941 --> 25:23.082
Anybody ever felt like that?

25:23.422 --> 25:24.864
Here's the crazy thing about it.

25:25.725 --> 25:28.989
God is actually the only one that has been cheated.

25:29.650 --> 25:32.012
He is the only one that has been mistreated.

25:32.252 --> 25:39.481
He is the only one that has been underappreciated because he is the only one worthy of anything.

25:40.081 --> 25:41.443
That's the great irony here.

25:41.823 --> 25:44.146
We feel disfavored by God.

25:45.218 --> 25:48.203
when God has been disfavored by us.

25:49.505 --> 25:52.209
That's what Romans 3 tells us in verses 11, 12.

25:52.249 --> 25:55.034
It says, none is righteous.

25:55.174 --> 25:55.875
No, not one.

25:55.915 --> 25:57.177
No one understands.

25:57.257 --> 25:58.319
No one seeks for God.

25:58.379 --> 25:59.541
All have turned aside together.

25:59.581 --> 26:01.143
They have become worthless.

26:01.244 --> 26:03.507
No one does good, not even one.

26:03.567 --> 26:06.171
Don't you see?

26:06.272 --> 26:10.258
Like we turn our backs on God.

26:11.682 --> 26:16.927
We turned our back on God before the thought ever even crossed our mind that he might have turned his back on us.

26:18.929 --> 26:21.331
So how does he respond to us when we do that to him?

26:22.453 --> 26:23.534
Does he smite us where we stand?

26:23.594 --> 26:26.076
Does he render judgment from afar?

26:27.217 --> 26:29.199
Does he condemn you to hell with no hope at all?

26:34.484 --> 26:34.544
No.

26:34.564 --> 26:34.905
I love it.

26:34.965 --> 26:40.210
His response in this story is the same response that he had in the last story.

26:42.082 --> 26:43.884
He just starts asking questions.

26:45.486 --> 26:49.230
In the past, anything is, he just starts asking questions that he already knows the answers to.

26:50.932 --> 26:53.975
But we ourselves have not yet answered.

26:55.177 --> 26:56.178
So what are the questions?

26:58.901 --> 26:59.662
He looks at Cain.

27:01.243 --> 27:02.705
And friend, I think he's looking at you.

27:05.648 --> 27:07.210
And he's asking you, why are you angry?

27:09.352 --> 27:10.834
Why are you angry?

27:10.946 --> 27:13.150
Is it because you didn't get what you thought you deserved?

27:15.193 --> 27:18.738
Is it because someone achieved that thing that you wanted?

27:18.758 --> 27:21.483
Is it because you feel like life's been unfair?

27:23.065 --> 27:24.427
Maybe it's not why are you angry.

27:24.468 --> 27:26.230
Maybe it's why is your face fallen?

27:27.232 --> 27:28.514
Why are you so downcast?

27:29.576 --> 27:30.978
Do you fear that you'll never be happy?

27:31.018 --> 27:32.961
Do you fear that I've forgotten you?

27:33.001 --> 27:35.445
Do you fear that I don't hear your prayers when they rise up to heaven?

27:35.465 --> 27:38.610
Do you fear that this is all there will ever be for you?

27:40.930 --> 27:52.204
The amazing thing about this story is it communicates to us the character and nature of God as we learn that God comes to us the same way He came to Cain.

27:53.165 --> 27:58.251
He comes reaching out, wanting to process and talk through it all.

27:58.311 --> 28:06.742
He comes asking questions and ultimately affirming for us that there is still favor for you too.

28:08.905 --> 28:10.066
This is the thing that wrecked me.

28:10.754 --> 28:18.163
because it is so easy in our modern age to look left and right and see what everybody else has and wonder why God would do that for them but not do it for us.

28:18.403 --> 28:21.207
And if the truth of this story is saying, he's got plenty to give.

28:21.247 --> 28:29.116
He literally, he says to Cain, he says, if you do well, will you not be accepted?

28:29.156 --> 28:33.581
You see, he's communicating, hey, bro, I've got favor to spare.

28:34.222 --> 28:37.066
I've got an inexhaustible well of blessing.

28:37.827 --> 28:38.968
So why are you worried?

28:39.469 --> 28:40.690
Why are you stressed?

28:40.866 --> 28:41.988
Why are you resentful?

28:42.288 --> 28:43.229
Why do you envy?

28:43.590 --> 28:45.432
I've got everything and more that you could want.

28:45.853 --> 28:47.535
So, hey, you didn't do it today.

28:47.555 --> 28:48.276
That's okay.

28:48.777 --> 28:49.938
Let's try again tomorrow.

28:50.279 --> 28:51.420
Let's try again the next day.

28:51.641 --> 28:53.003
Let's not give up right now.

28:53.203 --> 28:54.705
Let's just continue to go.

28:54.905 --> 28:56.327
Let's keep on walking.

28:56.347 --> 28:57.629
Let's keep on talking.

28:57.709 --> 28:59.371
Let's keep on processing.

28:59.411 --> 29:03.096
Let's not give up on the fact that there is favor enough for you all.

29:05.620 --> 29:10.226
God's position towards us as is true for Cain.

29:10.658 --> 29:11.839
It never changed.

29:12.480 --> 29:17.985
Like we don't deserve it, but a loving God is still beckoning and unlovely people to repent and come home.

29:18.566 --> 29:29.516
We don't deserve it, but a forgiving God is still seeking an unforgivable people because he can call them to forgiveness and bring them into right relationship.

29:29.736 --> 29:35.842
We don't deserve it, but Christ, the favorable has laid down his life for the unfavorable that we might receive blessing from God again.

29:35.862 --> 29:39.826
You see, God's position towards us has not changed.

29:40.130 --> 29:46.477
Let me just ask you then, has yours?

29:49.901 --> 30:00.973
If his position hasn't changed, if he looks at you and he loves you and he accepts you and he values you and he wants you, what's your position have to say in response?

30:03.156 --> 30:03.796
It's crazy.

30:04.437 --> 30:08.882
We see in the story that though God's position towards Cain has not changed,

30:09.058 --> 30:11.901
Cain's position towards God has changed.

30:12.582 --> 30:13.943
That's what we pick up as we keep reading.

30:13.963 --> 30:16.306
Look at verse 8, Cain spoke to Abel as brother.

30:16.366 --> 30:19.389
And when they were in the field, Cain rose up against his brother, Abel, and he killed him.

30:20.230 --> 30:22.312
Then the Lord said to Cain, where is Abel your brother?

30:23.173 --> 30:23.794
That interesting.

30:24.554 --> 30:28.058
It's the same question he asked Eve in the last chapter.

30:30.321 --> 30:31.242
He says, what have you done?

30:31.282 --> 30:35.506
The same question he asked Eve in the last chapter.

30:36.514 --> 30:39.199
The voice of your brother's blood is crying to me from the ground.

30:39.439 --> 30:43.346
And now you're cursed from the ground, which has opened its mouth to receive your brother's blood from your hand.

30:43.987 --> 30:47.653
When you work the ground, it'll no longer yield to you at strength.

30:47.673 --> 30:48.474
You shall be a fugitive.

30:48.675 --> 30:49.897
A wanderer on the earth.

30:50.037 --> 30:54.084
And so Cain said to the Lord, my punishment, it's greater than I can bear.

30:54.124 --> 30:56.468
Behold, you've driven me today away from the ground.

30:56.668 --> 30:58.151
And from your face, I shall be hidden.

30:58.171 --> 30:59.133
I'll be a fugitive.

30:59.153 --> 31:02.258
And a wanderer on the earth, whoever finds me, they're going to kill me.

31:05.826 --> 31:08.572
This story, it's so tragic for me.

31:09.834 --> 31:15.325
Because as I read it, I see something that I think we'd often miss.

31:16.588 --> 31:23.121
You see, if we were to ask people, just the general public, hey, what's the story of Cain and Abel about?

31:23.201 --> 31:25.746
Most people would look at us and they would just say, murder.

31:26.050 --> 31:26.571
It's about murder.

31:26.831 --> 31:27.692
One guy killed his brother.

31:28.052 --> 31:31.816
And they wouldn't be wrong because this is the first recorded murder in human history.

31:31.876 --> 31:33.878
We see Cain rise up and strike his brother down.

31:34.198 --> 31:40.765
And yet what's fascinating about it is it takes all of one sentence to explain that specific detail.

31:41.666 --> 31:47.011
But there are 20 sentences here over, over viewing this account of Cain's life.

31:47.552 --> 31:49.273
But one sentence given to murder.

31:49.333 --> 31:53.938
I'm not much of a true crime podcast guy, but that doesn't make for a really compelling arc.

31:54.178 --> 31:57.001
Like we don't see him concoct some maniacal plan.

31:57.122 --> 31:59.705
We don't see him brandish, some sort of murder weapon.

31:59.785 --> 32:01.587
He doesn't hide a body or flee the scene.

32:02.548 --> 32:06.873
He just looks at his brother and is like, hey man, you want to go for a walk?

32:06.893 --> 32:07.694
Bam, like it's over.

32:07.714 --> 32:10.538
You know, like that's all it takes for the murder to take place.

32:10.878 --> 32:15.523
And yet it begs the question for us then, if that's true, what is this about?

32:19.749 --> 32:21.010
I think it's about rivalry.

32:22.498 --> 32:24.521
I think this story is about rivalry.

32:24.581 --> 32:28.526
Two people competing in pursuit of the same goal.

32:28.786 --> 32:30.989
And you want to know why I think that's so very tragic.

32:33.832 --> 32:42.223
Because that which came wanted for the smile of God was not something he could earn.

32:43.304 --> 32:46.929
Because you can't earn what you already have.

32:46.949 --> 32:48.491
But it is something you can lose.

32:50.213 --> 32:50.834
And he does.

32:51.842 --> 32:52.443
and we did.

32:54.686 --> 33:00.254
All of us, like sheep have gone astray, each of us by way of our sin are subject to death.

33:00.355 --> 33:16.178
We have committed a criminal offense of our own, not murder like this, but we have committed that crime of sinning against a holy God, and therefore his right response to us is not unfairness, but fairness.

33:18.498 --> 33:24.485
because you may not think that God always gives you what you deserve, but third point, God always gives sin what it deserves.

33:26.427 --> 33:28.249
God always gives sin what it deserves.

33:29.631 --> 33:31.293
There are so many ironies in this story.

33:31.313 --> 33:32.895
I had to keep myself from writing.

33:33.696 --> 33:34.457
Isn't it ironic?

33:34.857 --> 33:35.518
Isn't it ironic?

33:35.538 --> 33:37.060
Because they're just all over the place, man.

33:37.080 --> 33:39.583
Like this whole story is one giant irony.

33:39.903 --> 33:45.810
But I think maybe the biggest one is that Cain's problem with God's unfairness and blessing ables actions

33:47.458 --> 33:52.324
is actually overcome by God's fairness in condemning his own.

33:53.325 --> 34:06.882
Like, here's the thing, despite what we might feel about being, about God being unfair or him being unjust or him being prejudiced against us, what we must know that the scriptures declare loud and clear is God is fair.

34:07.923 --> 34:08.624
He is fair.

34:09.625 --> 34:10.186
He is fair.

34:10.426 --> 34:15.472
He will deal with all sin, whether it is now or it is later.

34:16.193 --> 34:16.754
We know.

34:17.026 --> 34:23.833
He is not patient as some count patients, but he is desiring that all would come to the knowledge of his repentance.

34:23.853 --> 34:25.796
That's what 2 Peter 3 tells us.

34:26.416 --> 34:32.943
We know he's holy, he's righteous, he's just, and because that is true, he will not overlook a single offense.

34:32.983 --> 34:42.454
Doesn't matter how small, nor how big it is, every single offense is worthy of the same condemnation in that we have sinned against him.

34:42.514 --> 34:46.258
And here's why that's such a hard truth.

34:48.642 --> 34:53.607
There's no dealing with sin without dealing with us.

34:56.089 --> 35:08.461
Ephesians 2 verse 3 says, all of us lived among them at one time gratifying the cravings of our flesh and following its desires and thoughts like the rest of them.

35:09.522 --> 35:13.626
We were by nature deserving of wrath.

35:14.607 --> 35:17.650
Some translations say we are children of wrath.

35:18.690 --> 35:20.312
which feels so hard to read.

35:21.434 --> 35:25.119
If you're here for the first time, this can feel tough to stomach.

35:26.341 --> 35:32.990
And yet if it is, it means that we probably have an improper understanding of what wrath actually is.

35:33.812 --> 35:38.198
You see, wrath is not the opposite of love, as our world would say.

35:38.218 --> 35:43.826
Wrath is an expression of love in that

35:44.898 --> 35:49.344
It is loving to destroy that which seeks to hurt what you care about most.

35:50.645 --> 35:58.195
I never understood this more clearly than until I stood in a hospital room and I held my little 8-pound, 8-ounce baby boy in my hands.

35:59.036 --> 36:00.718
I learned a lot about myself in that moment.

36:01.620 --> 36:08.168
I learned the depth to which I could love someone that never did anything for me.

36:10.151 --> 36:12.754
And I also learned the links to which I would go.

36:13.954 --> 36:16.839
to protect him from anyone that would dare harm him.

36:18.462 --> 36:23.190
In that hospital room, I learned a lot about wrath, which is not wrong of God to feel.

36:23.410 --> 36:25.554
It is right of God to feel.

36:25.594 --> 36:28.259
That's why Cain is freaking out in this moment.

36:28.479 --> 36:32.907
He realizes like the rest of us, he is sinned against God, and he is deserving of his wrath.

36:33.147 --> 36:37.234
He wanted God to treat him fairly, and the minute God does, he cannot handle it.

36:37.826 --> 36:40.749
He literally says, my punishment is greater than I can bear.

36:40.809 --> 36:44.914
Behold, you've driven me today away from the ground.

36:45.154 --> 36:47.096
Your face from me shall now be hidden.

36:47.136 --> 36:48.658
Do you hear the panic?

36:49.319 --> 36:52.502
He literally, he says, I've been driven from the ground.

36:52.522 --> 36:59.910
That is so sad because what it tells us is Cain has just in this moment been robbed of his purpose.

36:59.930 --> 37:06.898
Again, mankind's God-given purpose as we see in Genesis 1 and Genesis 2 is that they would work the ground.

37:07.458 --> 37:09.986
that they would order chaos, that they would produce flourishing.

37:10.427 --> 37:15.001
And yet he just realized his sin is going to oppose his very own purpose.

37:15.221 --> 37:20.617
He says that he has been hidden from God's face, meaning he has been removed from God's presence.

37:20.637 --> 37:22.162
That was never the intent.

37:22.690 --> 37:27.736
We see that God would walk in the cool of the day seeking Adam Eve to stroll alongside.

37:27.776 --> 37:39.529
Any time you read about God walking with people, whether it's Noah or Enoch or Abraham, throughout the Old Testament, particularly in this book of Genesis, what he realizes it is articulating a depth of relationship to God that we were always meant to have.

37:40.410 --> 37:44.654
And yet he just said, I'm gonna be hidden from your face.

37:44.674 --> 37:46.717
I will not have your presence.

37:46.857 --> 37:50.000
I will not enjoy the comfort of your company.

37:50.080 --> 37:51.602
You see sin

37:51.810 --> 37:54.013
It costs him when it costs us.

37:54.174 --> 37:56.397
It costs him everything.

37:59.602 --> 38:04.769
That's why no matter how far you look or hard you search, no thing in this life will ever fulfill you.

38:05.731 --> 38:11.099
It doesn't matter if you climb to the heights of corporate success or you sit in the halls of power or you become internet famous.

38:11.760 --> 38:12.962
It'll never be enough for you.

38:13.663 --> 38:15.265
Some of you, you're experiencing that right now.

38:15.325 --> 38:17.649
Like you've arrived, achieved your dreams.

38:17.709 --> 38:21.234
You're sitting at that table which you have longed to have a seat

38:21.346 --> 38:25.832
And yet what you realize is, man, this is not what I thought it would be.

38:28.015 --> 38:31.099
And the reason for that is you weren't designed to represent those things.

38:31.139 --> 38:32.681
You were designed to represent God.

38:34.543 --> 38:39.609
That's why no matter who you know or call friend in life, no one will ever satisfy you.

38:40.751 --> 38:49.362
You can befriend billionaires, you can find the love of your life, you can put A-listers on speed dial, or you can serial date your way into the grave.

38:50.402 --> 38:51.724
No one will ever be enough.

38:53.566 --> 38:58.312
And the reason why is you weren't designed to relate to them, you were designed to relate to God.

39:01.796 --> 39:09.786
And here's the thing, though our sin rightly deserves God's wrath, surprisingly, that's not the end of the story.

39:10.948 --> 39:16.014
Because what we find in these final two verses is something that is truly unfair.

39:17.576 --> 39:19.058
It says, then the Lord said to him,

39:19.714 --> 39:20.315
Not so.

39:20.375 --> 39:25.821
If anyone kills Cain, the vengeance shall be taken on him sevenfold.

39:26.722 --> 39:29.606
And the Lord put a mark on Cain lest any who found him should attack him.

39:29.986 --> 39:34.451
And then Cain went away from the presence of the Lord and settled in the land of naught east of Eden."

